excerpt: Soaring Romanesque cathedral & site of pilgrimage known for Master Mateo's carved arched portico.
detail_description: The Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela is a magnificent Romanesque structure and a renowned pilgrimage site, featuring the impressive carved arched portico by Master Mateo. The cathedral has undergone various extensions and incorporates elements of Renaissance, Baroque, and Neo-Classical styles. Its different facades showcase diverse architectural influences, from Baroque to Neoclassical.
name: Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela
address: Praza do Obradoiro, s/n, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Traditional indoor/outdoor market with vendor stalls selling meats, flowers, produce & cheeses.
detail_description: Mercado de Abastos is a traditional market offering a wide variety of goods, including meats, flowers, produce, and cheeses. It is a must-visit destination to experience the famous food of Galicia. Visitors can indulge in the tempting smells and tastes of fresh seafood from the rias, local cheeses, Padron peppers, and renowned tapas. The market provides an authentic atmosphere where locals and tourists alike enjoy tapas on Calle Franco and Calle Raina.
name: Mercado de Abastos
address: Rúa das Ameas, s/n, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Lively main square in Santiago de Compostela's old town that's surrounded by notable buildings.
detail_description: Praza do Obradoiro is a bustling main square in the old town of Santiago de Compostela, surrounded by significant buildings such as Gelmirez Palace, San Jeronimo College, and the Monastery of San Martin Pinario. The square's grandeur is compared to historic plazas around the world and its four sides are said to represent different architectural styles and aspects of civic life.
name: Praza do Obradoiro
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Santiago de Compostela is the capital of northwest Spain’s Galicia region. It’s known as the culmination of the Camino de Santiago pilgrimage route, and the alleged burial site of the Biblical apostle St. James. His remains reputedly lie within the Catedral de Santiago de Compostela, consecrated in 1211, whose elaborately carved stone facades open onto grand plazas within the medieval walls of the old town.
detail_description: Santiago de Compostela, the capital of Galicia in northwest Spain, is renowned as the endpoint of the Camino de Santiago pilgrimage and the alleged resting place of St. James. The city's focal point is the Catedral de Santiago de Compostela, a grand medieval cathedral housing St. James' remains. Visitors can explore the Holy Land Museum showcasing over 700 artifacts from various eras and religions, including Christianity, Islam, and Judaism.
name: Santiago de Compostela
address: Municipality of Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Completed in 1776, this stately, French neoclassical palace serves as the seat of the city council.
detail_description: Pazo de Raxoi, a grand French neoclassical palace completed in 1776, stands as the city council's seat in Santiago. The Historic Center of Santiago boasts numerous remarkable buildings, including the Cathedral, Praza do Obradoiro, and Pazo de Raxoi.
name: Pazo de Raxoi
address: Praza do Obradoiro, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Stately museum & Romanesque cathedral with permanent & temporary exhibits of historic artworks.
detail_description: The Cathedral Museum is a grand museum housed within a Romanesque cathedral, featuring both permanent and temporary exhibits of historic artworks. The museum spans four floors and includes the cathedral's impressive 16th-century Gothic/plateresque cloister, showcasing Maestro Mateo's original carved-stone choir, religious art collection, lavishly decorated sala capitular, tapestries designed by Goya, and the Panteon de Reyes with tombs of medieval Leon kings.
name: Cathedral Museum
address: Praza do Obradoiro, S/N, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Complex of modern structures designed by a celebrated architect hosting exhibits, events & concerts.
detail_description: Cidade da Cultura de Galicia is a modern architectural complex in Santiago, designed by renowned architect Peter Eisenman. It hosts various exhibits, events, and concerts. While the old town of Santiago offers a traditional atmosphere with its winding streets and historic sites, the modern side can be seen around the university area and in art galleries. The Cidade da Cultura stands out as one of the most surprising examples of contemporary architecture in Galicia.
name: Cidade da Cultura de Galicia
address: Monte Gaiás, s/n, 15707 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Praza das Praterías is a charming square near the Cathedral, offering the best view of the bell tower, La Berenguela. The area around the Cathedral is full of delightful squares and monuments like the Monastery of San Martino Pinario. Even on the outskirts, places like Alameda Park and Monte do Gozo offer great views of the Cathedral. The latter features sculptures of pilgrims that have become iconic in photographs.
name: Praza das Praterías
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Baroque medieval Catholic church & monastery, with mass & a museum of historic art.
detail_description: The Monasterio de San Paio de Antealtares is a historic Benedictine monastery and church in Santiago de Compostela, Spain. Founded in the 11th century by Alfonso II to house monks guarding the tomb of St. James, it was later occupied by cloistered nuns dedicated to St. Pelayo. The monastery was virtually destroyed and rebuilt in the 17th and 18th centuries, featuring an image of San Paio on its facade.
name: Monasterio de San Paio de Antealtares
address: Rúa de San Paio de Antealtares, 23, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Art, exhibits & artifacts related to the history of pilgrimages to Santiago de Compostela.
detail_description: The Museum of Pilgrimage, also known as Museo das Peregrinacions e de Santiago, is a captivating destination in the Praza das Praterias. It offers a deep dive into the history of pilgrimages to Santiago de Compostela. The museum showcases an array of art, exhibits, and artifacts related to the epic pilgrimage towards Santiago that draws thousands of people annually.
name: Museum of Pilgrimage
address: Praza das Praterías, 2, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Now a refined hotel, this historic convent sits near a Gothic cathedral, museum & notable monuments.
detail_description: Convento de San Francisco de Santiago, originally a 13th-century monastery for Franciscan friars, has been transformed into a refined hotel and restaurant. The historic building is located near a Gothic cathedral and notable monuments. The former convent now offers excellent facilities, delicious food with a special Pilgrim menu featuring typical monastery dishes, and top-notch service.
name: Convento de San Francisco de Santiago
address: Rúa do Campiño de San Francisco, 3, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Pr. da Quintana de Vivos, also known as Quintana Square, is a historic site located at the confluence of the south facade of the cathedral, Parra House, Convent of San Paio de Antealtares and Conga house. This 16th-century space features characteristic steps and was historically used for public events including vindictive gatherings, entertainment, and popular concerts.
name: Pr. da Quintana de Vivos
address: Santiago de Compostela, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

name: Parque infantil da Alameda de Santiago
address: Av. de Antonio Raimundo Ibáñez, 14, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Tranquil park with shaded walkways, gardens, views of nearby landmarks & ruins of an old cemetery.
detail_description: Parque de San Domingos de Bonaval is a serene and picturesque park surrounded by Gothic and Baroque architecture. The lush hydrangea gardens, shaded woods, and well-maintained landscapes make it an ideal spot for a leisurely stroll or a peaceful picnic. From the lawn above the old monastic cemetery, visitors can enjoy perfect views of the nearby cathedral towers to the west. Additionally, the park offers beautiful vistas of Santiago and features a water fountain dating back to 1747.
name: Parque de San Domingos de Bonaval
address: Costa de San Domingos, 3, 15703 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Monastery featuring a grand interior, religious art museum & facade with a carved stone altarpiece.
detail_description: Located in the heart of Santiago's old quarter, Mosteiro de San Martiño Pinario is a must-visit destination for history and art enthusiasts. The monastery boasts a grand interior and houses a religious art museum. As you explore the surrounding area, you'll encounter the magnificent facade of the convent, adorned with a carved stone altarpiece, as well as a stunning Baroque twin staircase nearby.
name: Mosteiro de San Martiño Pinario
address: Pl. de San Martiño, S/N, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: 16th-century park with historical monuments & a garden featuring many ornamental trees & shrubs.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Santiago de Compostela, Parque da Alameda is a stunning 16th-century park that serves as a serene escape from the bustling city. This elegant green space comprises three distinct areas: Paseo da Alameda, the Oak Grove of Santa Susana, and Paseo da Ferradura. While its origins date back centuries, many of its enchanting features—like ornate fountains, tranquil ponds, and vibrant flower gardens—were added in the 19th century.
name: Parque da Alameda
address: Rúa do Campiño da Ferradura, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Fundación Eugenio Granell, also known as Pazo do Marqués de Bendaña, is a space dedicated to the surrealist painter from Coruna. Established in 1995, it houses a collection of Granell's works including oils, sculptures, drawings, and collages. The foundation also features pieces by other artists such as Miro, Lam, Caballero, Copley, and Duchamp.
name: Fundación Eugenio Granell / Pazo do Marqués de Bendaña
address: Praza do Toural, 8, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Casa do Cabildo, a prime example of Baroque architecture in Galicia, was constructed in 1758 and is celebrated for its stunning facade. Situated along the lower side of Praza das Praterias, this opulent aristocratic house boasts a temporary exhibition hall with free access. Currently showcasing an exhibit on Lorca and his time in Santiago, visitors are encouraged to explore the building's first floor recording and original drawings.
name: Casa do Cabido. Sala de Exposicións
address: Praza das Praterías, 6, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The Convent of San Domingos de Bonaval, dating back to the 14th century, showcases a blend of Gothic and Baroque architectural styles. The church features three naves adorned with arches and a charming chapel with a ribbed vault. Inside, visitors can explore four Gothic tombs and the burial sites of notable Galicians such as Rosalia de Castro, Alfredo Branas, and Ramon Cabanillas.
name: Convent of San Domingos de Bonaval
address: Costa de San Domingos, 15703 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Rúa do Franco, a lively street originating from the Cathedral, is renowned for its vibrant nightlife and exceptional tapas bars. Establishments like A Taberna do Bispo and Tapas Petiscos do Cardeal are highly recommended, but there are numerous other bars along this bustling thoroughfare that offer equally delightful culinary experiences.
name: Rúa do Franco
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The University of Santiago de Compostela is a must-visit gem nestled in the heart of Santiago. Founded by Benedictine monks in the 9th century, this historic institution boasts stunning Baroque architecture and an impressive wood-carved altarpiece that captivates visitors. The campus offers a tranquil escape with its lush green spaces, including the picturesque Parque da Alameda nearby.
name: University of Santiago de Compostela
address: Praza do Obradoiro, 0, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

name: Praza das Praterías (Santiago de Compostela)
address: 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Pazo de Xelmírez, located to the north of the cathedral, is a well-preserved palace built between 1120-1236. It offers visitors a glimpse into the city's history and culture from almost a thousand years ago. The palace is not a museum but serves as an impressive example of the city's heritage.
name: Pazo de Xelmírez
address: Praza do Obradoiro, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Strolling through the charming streets of Rúa do Vilar, Rúa do Franco, and Raina in the historic quarter offers a delightful experience. This area is home to tourist offices, the pilgrims center, and an array of shops selling everything from crafts and souvenirs to clothing and food. Visitors can also explore small book and antique markets while taking in the picturesque surroundings.
name: Rúa do Vilar
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: When visiting Santiago de Compostela, make sure to explore the stunning Obradoiro Square. This charming square is surrounded by architectural wonders such as the Royal Hospital (now a Parador hotel), the neoclassical Raxoi Palace, the mansion of San Xerome, and the Baroque facade of the cathedral. For a panoramic view of the city, head to Monte Pedroso which is visible from Obradoiro Square.
name: Obradoiro Square
address: Praza da Inmaculada, 2, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The Camino de Finisterre offers a challenging yet rewarding journey with breathtaking landscapes that never fail to impress. Along the way, there are numerous establishments where travelers can refuel with a variety of local products. The path is not only a physical challenge but also an opportunity for inner discovery. Hostels such as Casa Loncho, Casa Pepa, Albergue O Logoso, and Albergue Bela Muxia provide hospitality along the route.
name: Camino de Finisterre
address: Rua Sarela de Abaixo, 53, 15898 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Museum dedicated to Galician history & culture housed in a convent founded in the 13th century.
detail_description: The Museo del Pueblo Gallego is a captivating museum dedicated to the history and culture of Galicia, housed within a 13th-century convent complex. For a small fee, visitors can explore this impressive ethnographic museum featuring artifacts dating back to prehistoric times. The museum offers interactive exhibits and performances that bring Galician traditions to life. It provides an intriguing insight into the traditional culture of Galicia, showcasing trades, clothing, traditions, and the work of women.
name: Museum of the Galician People
address: Costa de San Domingos, 3, 15703 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: 1100s Romanesque church noted for its 18th-century flying buttresses & tilting interior columns.
detail_description: The Colegiata de Santa María de Sar is a remarkable 12th-century Romanesque church located in the outskirts of the city, next to the river Sar. It features a facade tower, flying buttresses added in the 18th century, and unique composite pillars supporting rib arches for natural lighting. The church has three basilical structures divided by pillars and showcases a leaning interior columns phenomenon.
name: Colegiata de Santa María de Sar
address: Rúa de Sar, s/n, 15701 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Museo Casa da Troia is a faithful recreation of a 19th-century student boarding house, which served as the inspiration for the popular novel La Casa de la Troya by Alejandro Perez Lugin. It offers an intriguing glimpse into the architectural style of old houses around the cathedral in centuries past. Open during Easter Week and summer, this museum provides a unique opportunity to step back in time and experience the ambiance of a bygone era.
name: Museo Casa da Troia
address: Rúa da Troia, 5, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Modern, kid-friendly natural history museum exhibiting a variety of mounted animal specimens.
detail_description: USC ~ Museo de Historia Natural is a modern and family-friendly natural history museum that showcases a diverse collection of mounted animal specimens, including marine animals, birds, and mammals. Additionally, the museum features sections dedicated to fossils, meteorites, and minerals. Visitors have the option to explore the museum at their own pace or join a guided tour. The entry fee is affordable for families and there are occasional free admission days.
name: USC ~ Museo de Historia Natural
address: Parque Vista Alegre, s/n, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Praza da Inmaculada is home to the baroque Casa do Cabildo, a stunning 3m-deep facade built in the 1750s. Located along the lower side of Praza das Praterias, this architectural gem is a must-see for visitors exploring the area.
name: Praza da Inmaculada
address: Santiago de Compostela, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Located just a short walk from Plaza de las Praterias, you'll find the charming Plaza de Fonseca. This square is surrounded by cozy cafes and offers a delightful view of the Colexio de Fonseca with its magnificent Renaissance courtyard. Dating back to 1495, this was once the main site of the Santiago university, adding historical significance to its already picturesque setting.
name: Praza de Fonseca
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Understated restaurant offering generous seafood dishes, including shrimp & crab meals.
detail_description: Taberna O Gato Negro is a modest yet legendary restaurant in Santiago, known for its generous seafood dishes and traditional Galician cuisine. The unassuming decor takes a back seat to the star of the show: the food. Many claim it's home to the best octopus in the world, making it a must-visit for any food enthusiast.
name: Taberna O Gato Negro
address: Rúa da Raíña, s/n, 15702 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Igrexa de Santa María do Camiño, a 13th-century church in Santiago de Compostela, boasts a neoclassical style. Adjacent to the church is Porta do Camino, known as the entrance to the city for pilgrims on the French route of Camino de Santiago. The church is well-preserved and has been a site for masses in various languages, including Italian.
name: Igrexa de Santa María do Camiño
address: A, R. Travesa, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Casa do Deán in Santiago de Compostela offers unguided visits lasting fifteen minutes, available from 7pm to 8pm Monday to Saturday. To secure one of the fifty free general-public tickets, visitors must go to the Fundacion Catedral office in Casa do Dean between 7pm and 8pm the day before their desired visit. The historic attraction boasts stunning architecture and a wealth of cultural heritage. Additionally, visitors can explore the peaceful garden on-site.
name: Casa do Deán
address: Rúa do Vilar, 1, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Galicia Querote Food Market SL, also known as Mercado de Abastos, is a beautiful 19th-century building located on Rua das Ameas in Santiago. It's a paradise for food lovers, offering the best seafood, fish, meat, cheese, and vegetables in the area. Visitors can enjoy a delightful culinary experience without needing reservations even during peak times.
name: Galicia Querote Food Market Sl
address: Rúa de Gómez Ulla, 1, 15702 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Rúa Nova is a charming street in Santiago de Compostela, known for its Renaissance cloister in Fonseca College. The college houses the library of the University of Santiago and is a must-see for visitors. Additionally, Rúa Nova offers a variety of bars and restaurants where you can take a leisurely break and enjoy some local cuisine at your own pace.
name: Rúa Nova
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The Confederación Española de Cascos Históricos is a vibrant district filled with charming streets and hidden squares, such as the Plaza de Cervantes, adorned with stunning statues and ornate fountains. The area buzzes with activity, offering the chance to stumble upon religious masses or processions as you wander through its ancient thoroughfares. Additionally, numerous inviting cafes and restaurants provide opportunities to savor authentic Spanish tapas while soaking in the lively atmosphere.
name: Confederación española de Cascos Históricos
address: Rúa da Algalia de Arriba, 31, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

name: Café del Parador de Santiago
address: Rúa das Carretas, 4, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Regional & international contemporary art showcased in a stark, minimalist interior.
detail_description: The Contemporary Art Center of Galicia (CGAC) is a must-visit for art enthusiasts, showcasing regional and international contemporary art in a sleek, minimalist setting. Located near the old town of Santiago, this museum features a permanent collection of works by prominent contemporary Galician and Spanish artists, as well as temporary exhibitions exploring various artistic currents and current cultural topics. The building itself is an architectural marvel.
name: Contemporary Art Center of Galicia
address: R. de Ramón del Valle-Inclán, 2, 15703 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

name: Igrexa de Santa María Salomé
address: Rúa Nova, 31, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: CSC Maruxa e Coralia is a long-awaited sociocultural venue located in the old town. It offers a wide range of activities and has been highly in demand since its opening. Visitors have expressed pleasant surprise at discovering this hidden gem, praising the variety of activities and the pleasant atmosphere. The venue has also received positive feedback for its excellent customer service and renovated space, making it a popular choice for locals looking to take advantage of what it has to offer.
name: csc maruxa e coralia
address: Praza de Salvador Parga, 4, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The "Porch of the Glory" is a significant feature of Santiago de Compostela Cathedral, located in Galicia, Spain. This Romanesque masterpiece greeted pilgrims upon their arrival and holds immense religious importance as it is believed to be the burial site of Saint James the Great. The cathedral also marks the end of the Camino de Santiago pilgrimage route. Visitors can explore its rich history and even gain optional entry to the Portico of Glory.
name: Porch of the Glory
address: Praza do Obradoiro, s/n, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Nestled just a stone's throw from the iconic Obradoiro, the Fountain of Horses, or Fuente de los Caballos, graces Praza de Plateras in Santiago de Compostela. This stunning baroque fountain, crafted in 1825 by J. Pernas, showcases four majestic horses elegantly pouring water from their mouths. Atop its pedestal sits a Marble Ark adorned with a female figure clutching the star of Compostela—an emblematic symbol of the city.
name: Fountain of Horses
address: Praza das Praterías, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The Palace of Fonseca, also known as Pazo de Fonseca, is a historic building in Santiago. Originally the ancestral home of Archbishop Alonso de Fonseca, it was transformed into the University of Compostela in 1544. The Renaissance-style palace features a stunning courtyard and a gothic chapel. Today, it serves as the General Library of the university and is open to visitors for free.
name: Palace of Fonseca
address: Rúa do Franco, s/n, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The Sargadelos Galería Santiago, formerly located on Rua Nova, has relocated to a new address. This store showcases and promotes the rich cultural heritage of Galicia, specifically through its collection of 19th-century ceramic artifacts from the renowned Ceramicas de Sargadelos. As a significant purveyor of Galician culture, it serves as both a retail establishment and a cultural hub.
name: Sargadelos Galería
address: Rúa do Doutor Teixeiro, 1, 15701 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: This museum traces the history of local education through artifacts, exhibits & replica classrooms.
detail_description: The Museo Pedagógico de Galicia is highly recommended for all visitors as it provides a comprehensive overview of the history of local education. The museum showcases various artifacts, exhibits, and replica classrooms that offer a glimpse into one of the most significant stages of cognitive and educational learning in Spanish society. It serves as a living memory and demonstrates the evolution of education in Spain. This institution presents an excellent opportunity to gain insight into how educational practices have developed over time within the Spanish state.
name: Museo Pedagógico de Galicia
address: Rúa de San Lázaro, 107, 15707 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Once part of the town's fortifications, this section of medieval wall features an arched opening.
detail_description: The Restaurant Arco de Mazarelos in Galicia offers exceptional cuisine and top-notch service. With its fresh, made-to-order dishes, patrons are treated to a delightful dining experience. Located near the Philosophy, History and Geography faculty, as well as the university church, this charming eatery is a convenient stop for tourists exploring the old city walls. After a long day of walking, visitors can unwind at nearby cafes before indulging in the restaurant's delicious offerings.
name: Restaurant Arco de Mazarelos
address: Praza de Mazarelos, 8, 15703 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain
